{"title_page": "Smoke on the Water", "text_new": "{{short description|1973 single by Deep Purple}}\n{{Redirect|Smoke On The Water|the song by Red Foley|Smoke on the Water (Red Foley song)}}\n{{Redirect|Some stupid with a flare gun|the Ass Ponys album|Some Stupid with a Flare Gun}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Smoke on the Water\n| cover      = Smoke on the Water.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Cover of the 1973 German single\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Deep Purple]]\n| album      = [[Machine Head (album)|Machine Head]]\n| B-side     = \"Smoke on the Water\" (live)\n| released   = May 1973\n| format     = [[7-inch record]]\n| recorded   = December 1971\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      =\n*[[Hard rock]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.prefixmag.com/news/vh1s-100-greatest-hard-rock-songs-list-only-slight/24504/ |title= VH1's 100 Greatest Hard Rock Songs list only slightly less annoying than their hip-hop list |author= Andrew Winistorfer |publisher= Prefix |accessdate= 1 July 2013 |url-status= live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130707023017/http://www.prefixmag.com/news/vh1s-100-greatest-hard-rock-songs-list-only-slight/24504/ |archivedate= 7 July 2013 |df= dmy-all }}<br />11 Deep Purple - \"Smoke On The Water\"</ref><ref>{{cite book |title= MusicHound rock: the essential album guide |author= Gary Graff |editor= Visible Ink Press |year= 1996 |isbn= 978-0787610371 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/musichoundrockes0000unse }} \"Purple's heyday came during the early 70s- when \"Smoke on the Water\" entered the pantheon of hard rock classics\"</ref>\n*[[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]]<ref>Christe (2003), pg. 13, \"'' Though Deep Purple's \"Smoke on the Water\" was a bona fide metal anthem and the first basic riff of a longhairded guitarist's repertoire, the band did not consider itself heavy metal.''\"</ref>\n| length     = {{ubl|5:41 (album version)|3:54 (single version)|6:15 (Roger Glover remix)}}\n| label      =\n*[[EMI]] (UK)\n*[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner. Bros]] (US)\n| writer     =\n*[[Ritchie Blackmore]]\n*[[Ian Gillan]]\n*[[Roger Glover]]\n*[[Jon Lord]]\n*[[Ian Paice]]\n| producer   = Deep Purple\n| prev_title = [[Never Before (song)|Never Before]]\n| prev_year  = 1972\n| next_title = [[Woman from Tokyo]]\n| next_year  = 1973\n| misc       = {{Extra track listing\n | album  = [[Machine Head (album)|Machine Head]]\n | type   = single\n | tracks = {{Machine Head tracks}}\n}}\n{{Audio sample\n | type = single\n | file = Deep_Purple_-_Smoke_on_the_Water.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Smoke on the Water'''\" is a song by the English [[rock music|rock]] band [[Deep Purple]]. It was first released on their 1972 album ''[[Machine Head (album)|Machine Head]]''. In 2004, the song was ranked number 434 on ''Rolling Stone'' magazine's list of [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Songs of All Time|the 500 greatest songs of all time]],<ref name=\"RollingStone\"/> ranked number 4 in ''[[Total Guitar]]'' magazine's Greatest Guitar Riffs Ever,<ref name=\"BBC\"/> and in March 2005, [[Q (magazine)|''Q'' magazine]] placed \"Smoke on the Water\" at number 12 in its list of the 100 greatest guitar tracks.<ref name=\"QMagazine\"/>\n\n==Composition==\n{{Original research|section|date=August 2019}}\n[[File:Smoke on the Water riff.jpg|thumb|left|The ''Smoke on the Water'' riff]] \"Smoke on the Water\" is easily identified by its central theme, developed by guitarist [[Ritchie Blackmore]]. It is a four-note [[blues scale]] melody in [[G minor]], harmonised in parallel fourths. The [[riff]], played on a [[Fender Stratocaster]] [[electric guitar]] by Blackmore, is later joined by hi-hat and distorted organ, then the rest of the [[Drum kit|drums]], then [[bass guitar|electric bass]] parts before the start of [[Ian Gillan]]'s vocal.\n\nBlackmore later claimed that the main power chord riff is an interpretation of inversion of [[Symphony No. 5 (Beethoven)|Symphony No. 5]] by [[Ludwig van Beethoven]], and that \"I owe him a lot of money\".<ref name=\"Thompson2004\">{{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Dave|title=Smoke on the Water: The Deep Purple Story|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LzzCw6xs9roC|year=2004|publisher=ECW Press|isbn=978-1-55022-618-8|page=128}}</ref>.  However, it is strikingly similar to the track \"Loose\" from [[The Stooges]] 1970 album ''[[Fun House (The Stooges album)|Fun House]]'', released the year before Smoke on the Water was written.  The guitar riffs from both songs also closely resemble a piano riff, played by [[Gil Evans]], from the 1966 [[Astrud Gilberto]] record \"Maria Quiet\"<ref>[http://www.whosampled.com/sample/view/33884/Deep%20Purple-Smoke%20on%20the%20Water_Astrud%20Gilberto%20and%20Gil%20Evans-Maria%20Quiet%20(Maria%20Moite)/ Deep Purple's Smoke on the Water sample of Astrud Gilberto and Gil Evans's Maria Quiet (Maria Moite). WhoSampled.com.]</ref>\n\nThe opening lyrics are:\n{{poemquote|We all came out to Montreux, on the Lake Geneva shoreline\nTo make records with a [[Rolling Stones Mobile Studio|mobile]], we didn't have much time}}\n\n[[Jon Lord]] doubles the guitar part on a [[Hammond organ|Hammond C3 organ]] played through a distorted Marshall amp, creating a tone very similar to that of the guitar. Blackmore usually plays the main riff using a finger pluck.<ref>{{Cite video\n |title       = Classic Albums - Machine Head\n |url         = http://www.veoh.com/browse/videos/category/entertainment/watch/v117567315egWJsXZ\n |publisher   = BBC\n |accessdate  = 30 October 2009\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110101134751/http://www.veoh.com/browse/videos/category/entertainment/watch/v117567315egWJsXZ\n |archivedate = 1 January 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref>{{Copyvio link|date=August 2019}}\n\nA performance by the original Mark II lineup was filmed in 1973 in colour during a US concert in New York City for [[Live in Concert 1972/73]]. Blackmore played the intro on the 3rd and 5th fret of a [[Sunburst (finish)|3 tone sunburst]] [[Fender Stratocaster]], often turning his back to the camera or the audience. Later on, he can be seen using his thumb top-down on the E and A strings on 8th and 10th fret, as follows:\n\n<pre style=\"display:inline-block\">-------------------------------------------\n-------------------------------------------\n-------------------------------------------\n------8-10-----8-11-10--------8-10--8------\n---10-8-10--10-8-11-10-----10-8-10--8-10---\n---10-------10-------------10---------10---</pre>\n\nThere are two solos in the song; the first was performed on guitar by Ritchie Blackmore, and the second was performed on an organ by Jon Lord until the song fades out.\n\n==History==\n{{quote box|width=27%|bgcolor=#FFFFF0|align=right|quote=We all came out to Montreux,<br />\nOn the Lake Geneva shoreline.<br />To make records with a mobile,<br />We didn't have much time.<br />Frank Zappa and the Mothers,<br />Were at the best place around.<br />But some stupid with a flare gun,<br />Burned the place to the ground.<br />Smoke on the water, fire in the sky.|source=\u2014Opening verse and chorus of \"Smoke on the Water\", recollecting the fire.}}\nThe lyrics tell a true story: On 4 December 1971, Deep Purple were in [[Montreux]], [[Switzerland]], to record an album using a mobile recording studio (rented from [[the Rolling Stones]] and known as the [[Rolling Stones Mobile Studio]]\u2014referred to as the \"Rolling truck Stones thing\" and \"a mobile\" in the lyrics) at the entertainment complex that was part of the [[Montreux Casino]] (referred to as \"the gambling house\" in the song lyric). On the eve of the recording session, a [[Frank Zappa]] and [[The Mothers of Invention]] concert was held in the casino's theatre. This was to be the theatre's final concert before the casino complex closed down for its annual winter renovations, which would allow Deep Purple to record there. At the beginning of [[Don Preston]]'s synthesizer solo on \"King Kong\", the place suddenly caught fire when somebody in the audience fired a [[flare gun]] toward the [[rattan]] covered ceiling, as mentioned in the \"some stupid with a flare gun\" line.<ref>''The Real Frank Zappa Book'' by Frank Zappa with Peter Occhiogrosso, pg. 112, {{ISBN|0-671-63870-X}}</ref><ref>''Bang Your Head'' by David Konow, page 26, {{ISBN|0-609-80732-3}}</ref> Although there were no major injuries, the resulting fire destroyed the entire casino complex, along with all the Mothers' equipment. The \"smoke on the water\" that became the title of the song (credited to bass guitarist [[Roger Glover]], who related how the title occurred to him when he woke from a dream a few days later) referred to the smoke from the fire spreading over [[Lake Geneva]] from the burning [[Montreux Casino|casino]] as the members of Deep Purple watched from their hotel. \"It was probably the biggest fire I'd ever seen up to that point and probably ever seen in my life\" said Glover. \"It was a huge building. I remember there was very little panic getting out, because it didn't seem like much of a fire at first. But, when it caught, it went up like a fireworks display.\" The \"Funky Claude\" running in and out is referring to [[Claude Nobs]], the director of the [[Montreux Jazz Festival]] who helped some of the audience escape the fire.<ref name=obit>{{cite web|title=Claude Nobs, Montreux Jazz Festival founder, dies|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-20981739|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=23 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Claude Nobs1.jpg|thumb|left|[[Claude Nobs]] (2006), the \"Funky Claude\" mentioned in the song]]\nLeft with an expensive mobile recording unit and no place to record, the band was forced to scout the town for another place to set up. One promising venue (found by Nobs) was a local theatre called The Pavilion, but soon after the band loaded in and started working/recording, neighbours took offence at the noise. The band was only able to lay down backing tracks for one song (based on Blackmore's riff and temporarily named \"Title No.1\"), before local police shut them down.<ref name=\u201cIndependent\u201d>{{cite news |title=How Deep Purple created their best hit 'Smoke on the Water' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/long_reads/deep-purple-montreux-jazz-festival-lake-geneva-1971-a8418926.html |accessdate=10 April 2020 |newspaper=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nAfter about a week of searching, the band rented the nearly-empty [[H\u00f4tel des Alpes-Grand H\u00f4tel|Grand H\u00f4tel de Territet]] and converted its hallways and stairwells into a makeshift studio, where they laid down most of the tracks for what would become their most commercially successful album, ''[[Machine Head (album)|Machine Head]]'' (which is dedicated to Claude Nobs).<ref>{{cite news |title=Deep Purple revient sur le lieu o\u00f9 est n\u00e9 \u00abSmoke on the Water\u00bb |url=https://www.tdg.ch/culture/musique/deep-purple-revient-smoke-the-water/story/29995483 |accessdate=10 April 2020 |work=Tribune deGeneve}}</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/sevenages/events/heavy-metal/deep-purple-release-machine-head/ Deep Purple release 'Machine Head'] BBC. Retrieved 19 October 2011</ref>\n\nThe only song from ''Machine Head'' not recorded entirely in the Grand Hotel was \"Smoke on the Water\" itself, which had been partly recorded during the abortive Pavilion session. Its lyrics were composed later, primarily by Gillan and based around Glover's title, and the vocals were recorded in the Grand Hotel.<ref name=\u201cIndependent\u201d/>\n\nBecause of the incident and the exposure Montreux received when \"Smoke on the Water\" became an international hit, Deep Purple formed a lasting bond with the town. The song is honoured in Montreux by a sculpture along the lake shore (right next to the statue of [[Queen (band)|Queen]] frontman [[Freddie Mercury]]) with the band's name, the song title, and the riff in musical notes. The new casino in Montreux displays notes from the riff as decoration on its balustrade facing the gambling hall.\n\nOn the ''[[Classic Albums]]'' episode about ''Machine Head'', [[Ritchie Blackmore]] claimed friends of the band were not fans of the \"Smoke on the Water\" riff, which they thought too simplistic. Blackmore retorted by making comparisons to the first movement of [[Symphony No. 5 (Beethoven)|Beethoven's 5th Symphony]], which revolves around a similar four note arrangement.\n\n\"The amazing thing with that song, and Ritchie's riff in particular,\" observed [[Ian Paice]], \"is that somebody hadn't done it before, because it's so gloriously simple and wonderfully satisfying.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|first=Paul|last=Rees|title=To Infinity\u2026 and Beyond?|magazine=[[Classic Rock (magazine)|Classic Rock]] #234|date=April 2017|p=39}}</ref>\n\n==Impact==\n{{more citations needed section|date=August 2019}}\n\"Smoke on the Water\" was included on ''Machine Head'', which was released in early 1972, but was not released as a single until a year later, in May 1973. (\"[[Never Before (song)|Never Before]]\" and \"[[Highway Star (song)|Highway Star]]\" were the first singles issued from the album.) The band members have said that they did not expect the song to be a hit, but the single reached number 4 on the Billboard pop singles chart in the United States during the summer of 1973, number 2 on the Canadian [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] charts, and it propelled the album to the top 10. Live performances of the tune, featuring extended interplay between Blackmore's guitar and [[Jon Lord]]'s [[Hammond organ]] would become a centrepiece of Deep Purple's live shows, and a version of the song from the live album ''[[Made in Japan (Deep Purple album)|Made in Japan]]'' became a minor hit on its own later on in 1973.\n\nThe principal songwriters included the song within their subsequent solo ventures after Deep Purple had split up. Ian Gillan in particular performed a jazz-influenced version in early solo concerts. The band [[Gillan (band)|Gillan]] adopted a feedback-soaked approach, courtesy of Gillan guitarist [[Bernie Torme]]. This song was also featured live by Ritchie Blackmore's post-Deep Purple band [[Rainbow (English band)|Rainbow]] during their tours 1981\u201383, and again after Rainbow was resurrected briefly in the mid-1990s and for three European concerts in June 2016.\n\nDuring Ian Gillan's stint with [[Black Sabbath]] in 1983, they performed \"Smoke on the Water\" as a regular repertoire number on encores during their only tour together. It remains one of the few cover songs that Black Sabbath has ever played live.\n\nThe song is popular amongst beginner guitarists, but Blackmore himself has demonstrated that most who attempt to play it do so improperly. Actually played using \"[[all fourths]]\" (or [[double stops]]) as specified by Blackmore, a [[power chord]]-driven variation on the main recognizable riff is not difficult, and is consequently often played by learners.\n\n\"Smoke on the Water\" has received the following rankings:\n* 434 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine's [[The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]] (2004)<ref name=\"RollingStone\">[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-20110407/deep-purple-smoke-on-the-water-19691231 500 Greatest Songs of All Time: Deep Purple, 'Smoke on the Water'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120703000445/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-20110407/deep-purple-smoke-on-the-water-19691231 |date=3 July 2012}} Rolling Stone. Retrieved 18 December 2011</ref>\n* 37 in [[VH1]]'s 40 Greatest Metal Songs<ref>''\"VH1 40 Greatest Metal Songs\"'', 1\u20134 May 2006, ''VH1'' Channel, reported by [http://www.vh1.com/shows/dyn/the_greatest/103446/episode_this_list.jhtml VH1.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229230728/http://www.vh1.com/shows/the_greatest/series.jhtml |date=29 February 2012}}; last accessed 10 September 2006.</ref>\n* 12 in [[Q (magazine)|''Q'' magazine's]] 100 Greatest Guitar Tracks (March 2005)<ref name=\"QMagazine\">[http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/qlistspage3.htm#Guitar Tracks 100 Greatest Guitar Tracks Ever!] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117184402/http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/qlistspage3.htm |date=17 January 2013}} Q Magazine. Retrieved 18 December 2011</ref>\n* 11 in VH1's \"''100 Greatest Hard Rock Songs''\" (January 2009)<ref>{{Cite web |title=spreadit.org music |url=http://music.spreadit.org/vh1-top-100-hard-rock-songs/ |accessdate=7 February 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220032159/http://music.spreadit.org/vh1-top-100-hard-rock-songs/ |archivedate=20 February 2012 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 4 in [[Total Guitar|''Total Guitar'' magazine]]'s \"Top 20 Greatest Guitar Riffs Ever\"<ref name=\"BBC\">{{citation |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3677965.stm |publisher=BBC News |date=2 May 2004 |accessdate=4 January 2010 |title=Guns N' Roses top rock riff poll |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814230144/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3677965.stm |archivedate=14 August 2009 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Chart history==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1973)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])\n|align=\"center\"|54\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|11|artist=Deep Purple|song=Smoke On The Water}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|27|artist=Deep Purple|song=Smoke On The Water}}\n|-\n|Canadian [[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'' Top Singles]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.4875&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=u9874ano8k0c5b6bkp4r8qrbp3 |title= Smoke on the water in Canadian Top Singles Chart |publisher= Library and Archives Canada |accessdate= 3 June 2013 |url-