{"title_page": "Joey Carbstrong", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Joey Carbstrong\n| image       = \n| birth_name  = Joseph Armstrong\n| birth_date  = {{birth-date and age|November 26, 1988}} <!--Dear fellow editors: To be verified-->\n| birth_place = [[Adelaide, Australia]]\n| nationality = Australian\n| occupation  = Animal rights activist\n| known_for   = Animals rights advocacy\n| website     = {{url|www.joeycarbstrong.com}}\n}}\n'''Joseph Armstrong''' (born November 26, 1988), known professionally as '''Joey Carbstrong''', is an Australian  [[Animal rights movement|animal rights activist]], vegan and former criminal.<ref name=\"Telegraph_DairyFarmersHitler2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/02/09/peaceful-vegan-activist-joey-carbstrong-compared-dairy-farmers/|title='Peaceful vegan activist' Joey Carbstrong compared dairy farmers to Hitler and told them to kill themselves|last=Hayley Dixon and Jonathan Pearlman|first=|date=9 February 2018|newspaper=The Telegraph|access-date=1 April 2018|publisher=Telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>  He is known for advocating for [[Animal rights|animal liberation]] and [[veganism]] through social media and public speaking engagements, as well as his debates on the [[ethics of eating meat]], especially during various televised interviews. \n\n== Personal life ==\nCarbstrong was born Joseph Armstrong in [[Adelaide]], Australia.<ref name=\"Telegraph_DairyFarmersHitler2\"/> He has publicly stated that before his fame he was involved in substance abuse and crime.<ref name=\"Telegraph_DairyFarmersHitler2\" /> He became vegan after his release from incarceration.<ref name=\"Telegraph_DairyFarmersHitler2\"/> He has a \u201cVegan\u201d tattoo behind his ear.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/article-thanks-to-vegans-my-vegetarianism-has-become-a-source-of-shame/|title=Thanks to vegans, my vegetarianism has become a source of shame|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> \n\nAt the age of 14 he had left school and developed a heavy [[Substance abuse|drug]] addiction.<ref name=\"Telegraph_DairyFarmersHitler2\"/> He had various blue collar jobs before receiving welfare at age 22. By this point he had gained a lengthy criminal record which included three assaults.<ref name=\"Telegraph_DairyFarmersHitler2\"/> He spent 18 months under house arrest. An arrest in September 2011 was the result of police discovering a concealed, loaded shotgun which Armstrong was bringing to a drug deal. Multiple weapons and additional ammunition in his hotel room were also discovered and he spent six months in jail.<ref name=\"Telegraph_DairyFarmersHitler2\"/> In May 2017, he released a video to celebrate his completion of four years as a teetotaler.<ref name=\"Telegraph_DairyFarmersHitler2\"/>\n\n== Animal rights advocacy == \n\nJoey has been involved in animal rights street activism in Australia, Hong Kong,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/article/2123837/hong-kong-pig-save-activists-stage-vigil-slaughterhouse-raise-awareness|title=Hong Kong Pig Save activists stage vigil at city slaughterhouse|date=2017-12-11|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> and the United Kingdom, promoting groups such as [[Anonymous for the Voiceless]] and the Save Movement, an organization that holds vigils outside abattoirs and aims to turn the world vegan by sharing images of the animals' treatment on social media.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-42833132|title='Vegans call me murderer and rapist'|last=Haque|first=Amber|date=2018-01-29|access-date=2019-11-13|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nDuring one protest against a slaughterhouse in [[Spennymoor|Spenymoor]], he stated, \"Slaughterhouses are usually on the outskirts of towns and hidden away. I am sure if they had glass walls not so many people would be eating flesh. We are here to bear witness to the animals being sent to slaughter. We take their photos and show them to the public so they know where the meat they are eating comes from. These animals are individuals and they want to live. We don\u2019t need meat to survive and we hope to make people think more about the food choices they make.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/15900775.celebrity-vegan-joey-carbstrong-stands-shoulder-to-shoulder-with-animal-rights-activists-during-abattoir-vigil-in-spenymoor/|title=Celebrity vegan stands shoulder-to-shoulder with animal rights activists during abattoir vigil|website=The Northern Echo|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\nCarbstrong has also commented that \"We can't love animals whilst we're consuming their flesh or paying for them to go into a slaughterhouse,\" and that \"Slaughterhouse workers are a product of a sick society who want to consume animal flesh.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===Debates===\n\nIn January 2018, he began a 'Vegan Prophecy UK tour', which involve protesting against multiple [[slaughterhouse]]s.<ref name=\"Telegraph_DairyFarmersHitler2\" /> During which he had multiple televised debates, including on the [[Jeremy Vine (TV programme)|Jeremy Vine Show]],<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/jeremy-vine-blasted-by-vegan-activist-offended-by-his-ham-and-cheese-sandwich_uk_5a72eb00e4b06fa61b4db202|title=Vegan Activist Blasts Jeremy Vine After Spotting His Ham And Cheese Sandwich|date=2018-02-01|website=HuffPost UK|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> [[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]],<ref name=\"Young 2018\">Young, Sarah. (2018). [https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/joey-carbstrong-vegan-campaigner-argument-this-morning-farming-couple-death-threats-criticism-a8196736.html \"Vegan campaigner Joey Carbstrong criticised after confronting farming couple who received death threats\"]. ''The Independent''. Retrieved 2019-11-13.</ref> and [[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5uqh_LNpay4&t=27s Is Milk Murder for Cows? | Good Morning Britain]. Retrieved 2019-11-13.</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Armstrong appeared on the British TV programme [[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]] to debate farmers Jonny and Dulcie Crickmore.<ref name=\"Young 2018\"/> Armstrong argued that artificial insemination in female cows is a form of [[sexual abuse]] and the [[Dairy farming|dairy]] industry \"sexually violates\" cows.<ref name=\"Young 2018\"/> On the [[Jeremy Vine (TV programme)|Jeremy Vine Show]] Armstrong criticized Vine's ham and cheese sandwich that was on his desk.<ref name=\":2\"/><ref>Street-Porter, Janet. (2018). [https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/vegans-veganism-ham-sandwich-jeremy-vine-show-a8190646.html \"Vegans hurt their case by being too extreme\"]. ''The Independent''. Retrieved 2019-11-13.</ref> Carbstrong stated that \"cheese comes from a mother who had her children taken from her, and had hands shoved in her anus and was artificially inseminated with bull semen. Probably why vegans would say that a dairy farmer is akin to a rapist. I wouldn\u2019t call a farmer a rapist, I wouldn\u2019t use any of those words without explaining to them the process and why they involve themselves in these types of practices.\"<ref name=\":2\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Veganism]]\n*[[Animal rights]]\n*[[List of animal rights advocates]]\n*[[List of vegans]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links==\n* [http://www.JoeyCarbstrong.com Official website]\n{{Portal bar|Animals}}\n{{Animal rights}}\n{{Vegetarianism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carbstrong, Joey}}\n\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian activists]]\n[[Category:Australian people convicted of assault]]\n[[Category:Australian educators]]\n[[Category:Animal rights activists]]\n[[Category:Veganism activists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Joey Carbstrong\n| image       = \n| birth_name  = Joseph Armstrong\n| birth_date  = {{birth-date and age|November 26, 1988}} <!--Dear fellow editors: To be verified-->\n| birth_place = [[Adelaide, Australia]]\n| nationality = Australian\n| occupation  = Animal rights activist\n| known_for   = Animals rights advocacy\n| website     = {{url|www.joeycarbstrong.com}}\n}}\n'''Joseph Armstrong''' (born November 26, 1988), known professionally as '''Joey Carbstrong''', is an Australian  [[Animal rights movement|animal rights activist]], vegan and former criminal.<ref name=\"Telegraph_DairyFarmersHitler2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/02/09/peaceful-vegan-activist-joey-carbstrong-compared-dairy-farmers/|title='Peaceful vegan activist' Joey Carbstrong compared dairy farmers to Hitler and told them to kill themselves|last=Hayley Dixon and Jonathan Pearlman|first=|date=9 February 2018|newspaper=The Telegraph|access-date=1 April 2018|publisher=Telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>  He is known for advocating for [[Animal rights|animal liberation]] and [[veganism]] through social media and public speaking engagements, as well as his debates on the [[ethics of eating meat]], especially during various televised interviews. \n\n== Personal life ==\nCarbstrong was born Joseph Armstrong in [[Adelaide]], Australia.<ref name=\"Telegraph_DairyFarmersHitler2\"/> He has publicly stated that before his fame he was involved in substance abuse and crime.<ref name=\"Telegraph_DairyFarmersHitler2\" /> He became [[Veganism|vegan]] after his release from incarceration.<ref name=\"Telegraph_DairyFarmersHitler2\"/> He has a \u201cVegan\u201d tattoo behind his ear.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/article-thanks-to-vegans-my-vegetarianism-has-become-a-source-of-shame/|title=Thanks to vegans, my vegetarianism has become a source of shame|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> \n\nAt the age of 14 he had left school and developed a heavy [[Substance abuse|drug]] addiction.<ref name=\"Telegraph_DairyFarmersHitler2\"/> He had various blue collar jobs before receiving welfare at age 22. By this point he had gained a lengthy criminal record which included three assaults.<ref name=\"Telegraph_DairyFarmersHitler2\"/> He spent 18 months under house arrest. An arrest in September 2011 was the result of police discovering a concealed, loaded shotgun which Armstrong was bringing to a drug deal. Multiple weapons and additional ammunition in his hotel room were also discovered and he spent six months in jail.<ref name=\"Telegraph_DairyFarmersHitler2\"/> In May 2017, he released a video to celebrate his completion of four years as a teetotaler.<ref name=\"Telegraph_DairyFarmersHitler2\"/>\n\n== Animal rights advocacy == \n\nJoey has been involved in animal rights street activism in Australia, Hong Kong,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/lifestyle/article/2123837/hong-kong-pig-save-activists-stage-vigil-slaughterhouse-raise-awareness|title=Hong Kong Pig Save activists stage vigil at city slaughterhouse|date=2017-12-11|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> and the United Kingdom, promoting groups such as [[Anonymous for the Voiceless]] and the Save Movement, an organization that holds vigils outside abattoirs and aims to turn the world vegan by sharing images of the animals' treatment on social media.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-42833132|title='Vegans call me murderer and rapist'|last=Haque|first=Amber|date=2018-01-29|access-date=2019-11-13|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nDuring one protest against a slaughterhouse in [[Spennymoor|Spenymoor]], he stated, \"Slaughterhouses are usually on the outskirts of towns and hidden away. I am sure if they had glass walls not so many people would be eating flesh. We are here to bear witness to the animals being sent to slaughter. We take their photos and show them to the public so they know where the meat they are eating comes from. These animals are individuals and they want to live. We don\u2019t need meat to survive and we hope to make people think more about the food choices they make.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/15900775.celebrity-vegan-joey-carbstrong-stands-shoulder-to-shoulder-with-animal-rights-activists-during-abattoir-vigil-in-spenymoor/|title=Celebrity vegan stands shoulder-to-shoulder with animal rights activists during abattoir vigil|website=The Northern Echo|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\nCarbstrong has also commented that \"We can't love animals whilst we're consuming their flesh or paying for them to go into a slaughterhouse,\" and that \"Slaughterhouse workers are a product of a sick society who want to consume animal flesh.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n===Debates===\n\nIn January 2018, he began a 'Vegan Prophecy UK tour', which involve protesting against multiple [[slaughterhouse]]s.<ref name=\"Telegraph_DairyFarmersHitler2\" /> During which he had multiple televised debates, including on the [[Jeremy Vine (TV programme)|Jeremy Vine Show]],<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/jeremy-vine-blasted-by-vegan-activist-offended-by-his-ham-and-cheese-sandwich_uk_5a72eb00e4b06fa61b4db202|title=Vegan Activist Blasts Jeremy Vine After Spotting His Ham And Cheese Sandwich|date=2018-02-01|website=HuffPost UK|language=en|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> [[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]],<ref name=\"Young 2018\">Young, Sarah. (2018). [https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/joey-carbstrong-vegan-campaigner-argument-this-morning-farming-couple-death-threats-criticism-a8196736.html \"Vegan campaigner Joey Carbstrong criticised after confronting farming couple who received death threats\"]. ''The Independent''. Retrieved 2019-11-13.</ref> and [[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5uqh_LNpay4&t=27s Is Milk Murder for Cows? | Good Morning Britain]. Retrieved 2019-11-13.</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Armstrong appeared on the British TV programme [[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]] to debate farmers Jonny and Dulcie Crickmore.<ref name=\"Young 2018\"/> Armstrong argued that artificial insemination in female cows is a form of [[sexual abuse]] and the [[Dairy farming|dairy]] industry \"sexually violates\" cows.<ref name=\"Young 2018\"/> On the [[Jeremy Vine (TV programme)|Jeremy Vine Show]] Armstrong criticized Vine's ham and cheese sandwich that was on his desk.<ref name=\":2\"/><ref>Street-Porter, Janet. (2018). [https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/vegans-veganism-ham-sandwich-jeremy-vine-show-a8190646.html \"Vegans hurt their case by being too extreme\"]. ''The Independent''. Retrieved 2019-11-13.</ref> Carbstrong stated that \"cheese comes from a mother who had her children taken from her, and had hands shoved in her anus and was artificially inseminated with bull semen. Probably why vegans would say that a dairy farmer is akin to a rapist. I wouldn\u2019t call a farmer a rapist, I wouldn\u2019t use any of those words without explaining to them the process and why they involve themselves in these types of practices.\"<ref name=\":2\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Veganism]]\n*[[Animal rights]]\n*[[List of animal rights advocates]]\n*[[List of vegans]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links==\n* [http://www.JoeyCarbstrong.com Official website]\n{{Portal bar|Animals}}\n{{Animal rights}}\n{{Vegetarianism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carbstrong, Joey}}\n\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian activists]]\n[[Category:Australian people convicted of assault]]\n[[Category:Australian educators]]\n[[Category:Animal rights activists]]\n[[Category:Veganism activists]]\n", "name_user": "Psychologist Guy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life:already linked, remove overlinking", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joey_Carbstrong"}
{"title_page": "Ragy Thomas", "text_new": "{{Short description|Ragy Thomas is an executive and serial entrepreneur, best known as CEO of Sprinklr}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name         = Ragy Thomas\n|image        = Ragy_Thomas_photo.jpg\n|alt          = Ragy Thomas Photo\n|birth_date   = \n|nationality  = \n|alma_mater   = [[New York University Stern School of Business]], M.B.A<br/> [[Pondicherry Engineering College]], Computer Science Engineering<ref name=crunch1>{{cite web|url=https://www.crunchbase.com/person/ragy-thomas#section-overview |title=Ragy Thomas|website=Crunchbase |date=|accessdate=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n|occupation   = CEO and founder of customer experience management software provider [[Sprinklr]]\n|known for    = executive, serial entrepreneur. CEO and founder of [[Sprinklr]]\n|years_active = \n|spouse       = \n|parents      = \n}}\n\nNot available!'''Ragy Thomas''' is an executive and serial entrepreneur, who is CEO of [[Sprinklr]], a SaaS company that develops a customer experience management platform.<ref name=crunch1/> He was previously president of Epsilon Interactive, now part of advertising network [[Publicis]], and founded email marketing company [[Bigfoot International#Bigfoot Interactive|Bigfoot Interactive]].<ref name=prweek1>{{cite web|url= https://www.prweek.com/article/1675857/tech-talk-sprinklr-founder-ceo-ragy-thomas |title=Tech Talk with Sprinklr Founder and CEO Ragy Thomas|website=PR Week |date=2020-03-04 |accessdate=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== Education and early life ==\nThomas was born and grew up in Kerala in India, the son of academic parents who uprooted and moved frequently. Thomas' parents moved to Nigeria for work when he was in the third grade.<ref name=forbes1>{{cite web|url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/brucerogers/2017/02/06/how-ragy-thomas-built-sprinklr-into-social-media-management-powerhouse/#7b3f7004d690 |title=How Ragy Thomas Built Sprinklr Into A Social Media Management Powerhouse |website=Forbes |date=2017-02-06 |accessdate=2020-03-22}}</ref> When Thomas was in the fifth grade, his parents returned to India and enrolled him in boarding school.<ref name=nytimes1>{{cite web|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/17/business/ragy-thomas-of-sprinklr-how-naivete-can-become-a-strength.html |title=Ragy Thomas of Sprinklr: How Na\u00efvet\u00e9 Can Become a Strength |website=NY Times |date=2016-01-14 |accessdate=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nHe attended [[Pondicherry Engineering College]] in India, and earned a degree in Computer Science Engineering. In 1996, while working for international consultancy Tata Unisys (now [[Tata Consultancy Services]]) he came to Wisconsin in the United States.<ref name=forbes2>{{cite web|url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/alexkonrad/2016/01/20/meet-sprinklr-the-startup-that-cracked-social/#3d45e2b1a23e |title=Meet Sprinklr, The Billion-Dollar Startup That Cracked Social Advertising |website=Forbes |date=2016-01-20 |accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref>  He then moved to New Jersey to do IT consulting for AT&T and Bell Labs, and worked for a dot com startup during the boom of 2000.<ref name=forbes2/> He attended [[New York University Stern School of Business]] part-time and earned his MBA in Finance and Information Systems.<ref name=forbes1/>\n\n==Career==\n===Bigfoot Interactive/Epsilon Interactive===\nAfter the dot-com bubble burst, Thomas co-founded an email marketing company that became [[Bigfoot International#Bigfoot Interactive|Bigfoot Interactive]].<ref name=forbes1/> Thomas served first as CTO. In 2005, the company was acquired by marketing services company Alliance Data, and was renamed Epsilon Interactive.<ref name=american1>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanbanker.com/news/in-brief-alliance-data-to-buy-bigfoot-interactive|title=In Brief: Alliance Data to Buy Bigfoot Interactive |website=American Banker|date=2005-09-09 |accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref>  In 2006, Thomas became president of Epsilon Interactive.<ref name=InfoWorld1>{{cite web|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=KzkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA62&lpg=PA62&dq=bigfoot+thomas+ragy&source=bl&ots=VvrKvvJHna&sig=ACfU3U1KabPfHaw8Sqiq8UcA5ffoglEXaA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiCgZ307anoAhWiJDQIHWh1B_8Q6AEwGXoECBcQAQ#v=onepage&q=bigfoot%20thomas%20ragy&f=false|title=Fostering a CTO Community |website=InfoWorld|date=2002-02-18 |accessdate=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref name=dmnews1>{{cite web|url= https://www.dmnews.com/marketing-channels/email/news/13070019/ragy-thomas-succeeds-ousted-ceo-al-diguido-at-epsilon-interactive|title=Ragy Thomas Succeeds Ousted CEO Al DiGuido at Epsilon Interactive |website=DMNews|date=2006-09-27 |accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref> At Epsilon, he oversaw the technical integration between Bigfoot and DoubleClick Email Solutions, acquired from online advertising company [[DoubleClick]] in 2006.<ref name=digital1>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalcommerce360.com/2006/02/14/epsilon-to-acquire-doubleclick-email-solutions-for-90-million/|title=Epsilon to acquire DoubleClick Email Solutions for $90 million |website=Digital Commerce 360|date=2006-02-14 |accessdate=2020-03-25}}</ref>  He left Epsilon Interactive in 2008.<ref name=chief1>{{cite web|url=https://www.chiefmarketer.com/exclusive-ragy-thomas-out-at-epsilon/|title=Exclusive: Ragy Thomas Out at Epsilon |website=Chief Marketer|date=2008-04-16 |accessdate=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n===Sprinklr===\n{{main|Sprinklr}}\n\nIn 2009, Thomas founded social media and customer management company Sprinklr, and serves as its CEO.<ref name=cnn1>{{cite web|url= https://money.cnn.com/interactive/technology/15-questions-with-ragy-thomas/|title=15 Questions with Ragy Thomas |website=CNN|date=|accessdate=2020-03-20}}</ref> Also in 2009, Thomas co-founded an Indian subsidiary Sprinkr India, which was later renamed Kenscio.<ref name=india1>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatechonline.com/it-for-you.php?id=326|title=India digital marketing pioneer, Kenscio, targets 5x growth |website=India Tech Online|date=2011-10-15 |accessdate=2020-03-24}}</ref>  Thomas is on the Kenscio board.<ref name=\"yale1\">{{cite web|url=https://som.yale.edu/event/2016/05/conversation-with-ragy-thomas-ceo-founder-sprinklr|title=Sprinklr CEO Ragy Thomas Discusses Marketing in the Age of Social Media|date=2010-10-08|website=Yale School of Management|accessdate=2020-03-25}}</ref> By July 2016, Sprinklr was valued at $1.8 billion, giving it [[Unicorn (finance)|Unicorn]] status.<ref name=wsj2>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/sprinklr-raises-105-million-to-grow-social-media-management-software-1469016062 |title=Sprinklr Raises $105 Million to Grow Social Media Management Software|website=Wall Street Journal |date=2016-07-21 |accessdate=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n===Entertainment producing===\nThomas was a producer of the 2015 Indian Malayalam language film [[Ennu Ninte Moideen]], directed by [[RS Vimal]].<ref name=battery1>{{cite web|url=https://www.battery.com/powered/five-questions-five-minutes-ceo-sprinklr/  |title=Five Questions in Five Minutes with the CEO of Sprinklr|website=Battery |date=2018-03-24 |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref> He also co-produced [[The Parisian Woman]], a Broadway play starring actress [[Uma Thurmond]].<ref name=battery1/><ref name=broadway1>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/shows/creative.php?showid=332251  |title=The Parisian Woman - Broadway Creative Team|website=Broadway World |date= |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\nThomas is also on the board of Cloth, a mobile fashion application company.<ref name=yale1/>\n\n== Honors and recognition ==\nIn 2010, Thomas was honored by the Indian American Kerala Cultural and Civic Centre for his achievements.<ref name=twocircles1>{{cite web|url=http://twocircles.net/2010nov08/kerala_centre_honours_5_indian_american_malayalees.html |title=Kerala Centre honours 5 Indian American Malayalee|website=Two Circles|date=2010-10-08 |accessdate=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n* \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas, Ragy}}\n[[Category:American technology chief executives]]\n[[Category:New York University Stern School of Business alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Ragy Thomas is an executive and serial entrepreneur, best known as CEO of Sprinklr}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name         = Ragy Thomas\n|image        = Ragy_Thomas_photo.jpg\n|alt          = Ragy Thomas Photo\n|birth_date   = \n|nationality  = \n|alma_mater   = [[New York University Stern School of Business]], M.B.A<br/> [[Pondicherry Engineering College]], Computer Science Engineering<ref name=crunch1>{{cite web|url=https://www.crunchbase.com/person/ragy-thomas#section-overview |title=Ragy Thomas|website=Crunchbase |date=|accessdate=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n|occupation   = CEO and founder of customer experience management software provider [[Sprinklr]]\n|known for    = executive, serial entrepreneur. CEO and founder of [[Sprinklr]]\n|years_active = \n|spouse       = \n|parents      = \n}}\n\n'''Ragy Thomas''' is an executive and serial entrepreneur, who is CEO of [[Sprinklr]], a SaaS company that develops a customer experience management platform.<ref name=crunch1/> He was previously president of Epsilon Interactive, now part of advertising network [[Publicis]], and founded email marketing company [[Bigfoot International#Bigfoot Interactive|Bigfoot Interactive]].<ref name=prweek1>{{cite web|url= https://www.prweek.com/article/1675857/tech-talk-sprinklr-founder-ceo-ragy-thomas |title=Tech Talk with Sprinklr Founder and CEO Ragy Thomas|website=PR Week |date=2020-03-04 |accessdate=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== Education and early life ==\nThomas was born and grew up in Kerala in India, the son of academic parents who uprooted and moved frequently. Thomas' parents moved to Nigeria for work when he was in the third grade.<ref name=forbes1>{{cite web|url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/brucerogers/2017/02/06/how-ragy-thomas-built-sprinklr-into-social-media-management-powerhouse/#7b3f7004d690 |title=How Ragy Thomas Built Sprinklr Into A Social Media Management Powerhouse |website=Forbes |date=2017-02-06 |accessdate=2020-03-22}}</ref> When Thomas was in the fifth grade, his parents returned to India and enrolled him in boarding school.<ref name=nytimes1>{{cite web|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/17/business/ragy-thomas-of-sprinklr-how-naivete-can-become-a-strength.html |title=Ragy Thomas of Sprinklr: How Na\u00efvet\u00e9 Can Become a Strength |website=NY Times |date=2016-01-14 |accessdate=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\nHe attended [[Pondicherry Engineering College]] in India, and earned a degree in Computer Science Engineering. In 1996, while working for international consultancy Tata Unisys (now [[Tata Consultancy Services]]) he came to Wisconsin in the United States.<ref name=forbes2>{{cite web|url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/alexkonrad/2016/01/20/meet-sprinklr-the-startup-that-cracked-social/#3d45e2b1a23e |title=Meet Sprinklr, The Billion-Dollar Startup That Cracked Social Advertising |website=Forbes |date=2016-01-20 |accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref>  He then moved to New Jersey to do IT consulting for AT&T and Bell Labs, and worked for a dot com startup during the boom of 2000.<ref name=forbes2/> He attended [[New York University Stern School of Business]] part-time and earned his MBA in Finance and Information Systems.<ref name=forbes1/>\n\n==Career==\n===Bigfoot Interactive/Epsilon Interactive===\nAfter the dot-com bubble burst, Thomas co-founded an email marketing company that became [[Bigfoot International#Bigfoot Interactive|Bigfoot Interactive]].<ref name=forbes1/> Thomas served first as CTO. In 2005, the company was acquired by marketing services company Alliance Data, and was renamed Epsilon Interactive.<ref name=american1>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanbanker.com/news/in-brief-alliance-data-to-buy-bigfoot-interactive|title=In Brief: Alliance Data to Buy Bigfoot Interactive |website=American Banker|date=2005-09-09 |accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref>  In 2006, Thomas became president of Epsilon Interactive.<ref name=InfoWorld1>{{cite web|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=KzkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA62&lpg=PA62&dq=bigfoot+thomas+ragy&source=bl&ots=VvrKvvJHna&sig=ACfU3U1KabPfHaw8Sqiq8UcA5ffoglEXaA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiCgZ307anoAhWiJDQIHWh1B_8Q6AEwGXoECBcQAQ#v=onepage&q=bigfoot%20thomas%20ragy&f=false|title=Fostering a CTO Community |website=InfoWorld|date=2002-02-18 |accessdate=2020-03-25}}</ref><ref name=dmnews1>{{cite web|url= https://www.dmnews.com/marketing-channels/email/news/13070019/ragy-thomas-succeeds-ousted-ceo-al-diguido-at-epsilon-interactive|title=Ragy Thomas Succeeds Ousted CEO Al DiGuido at Epsilon Interactive |website=DMNews|date=2006-09-27 |accessdate=2020-03-23}}</ref> At Epsilon, he oversaw the technical integration between Bigfoot and DoubleClick Email Solutions, acquired from online advertising company [[DoubleClick]] in 2006.<ref name=digital1>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalcommerce360.com/2006/02/14/epsilon-to-acquire-doubleclick-email-solutions-for-90-million/|title=Epsilon to acquire DoubleClick Email Solutions for $90 million |website=Digital Commerce 360|date=2006-02-14 |accessdate=2020-03-25}}</ref>  He left Epsilon Interactive in 2008.<ref name=chief1>{{cite web|url=https://www.chiefmarketer.com/exclusive-ragy-thomas-out-at-epsilon/|title=Exclusive: Ragy Thomas Out at Epsilon |website=Chief Marketer|date=2008-04-16 |accessdate=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n===Sprinklr===\n{{main|Sprinklr}}\n\nIn 2009, Thomas founded social media and customer management company Sprinklr, and serves as its CEO.<ref name=cnn1>{{cite web|url= https://money.cnn.com/interactive/technology/15-questions-with-ragy-thomas/|title=15 Questions with Ragy Thomas |website=CNN|date=|accessdate=2020-03-20}}</ref> Also in 2009, Thomas co-founded an Indian subsidiary Sprinkr India, which was later renamed Kenscio.<ref name=india1>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiatechonline.com/it-for-you.php?id=326|title=India digital marketing pioneer, Kenscio, targets 5x growth |website=India Tech Online|date=2011-10-15 |accessdate=2020-03-24}}</ref>  Thomas is on the Kenscio board.<ref name=yale1/> By July 2016, Sprinklr was valued at $1.8 billion, giving it [[Unicorn (finance)|Unicorn]] status.<ref name=wsj2>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/sprinklr-raises-105-million-to-grow-social-media-management-software-1469016062 |title=Sprinklr Raises $105 Million to Grow Social Media Management Software|website=Wall Street Journal |date=2016-07-21 |accessdate=2020-03-24}}</ref>\n\n===Entertainment producing===\nThomas was a producer of the 2015 Indian Malayalam language film [[Ennu Ninte Moideen]], directed by [[RS Vimal]].<ref name=battery1>{{cite web|url=https://www.battery.com/powered/five-questions-five-minutes-ceo-sprinklr/  |title=Five Questions in Five Minutes with the CEO of Sprinklr|website=Battery |date=2018-03-24 |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref> He also co-produced [[The Parisian Woman]], a Broadway play starring actress [[Uma Thurmond]].<ref name=battery1/><ref name=broadway1>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/shows/creative.php?showid=332251  |title=The Parisian Woman - Broadway Creative Team|website=Broadway World |date= |accessdate=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\nThomas is also on the board of Cloth, a mobile fashion application company.<ref name=yale1/>\n\n== Honors and recognition ==\nIn 2010, Thomas was honored by the Indian American Kerala Cultural and Civic Centre for his achievements.<ref name=twocircles1>{{cite web|url=http://twocircles.net/2010nov08/kerala_centre_honours_5_indian_american_malayalees.html |title=Kerala Centre honours 5 Indian American Malayalee|website=Two Circles|date=2010-10-08 |accessdate=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nThomas lives in New Jersey with his wife and two children.<ref name=yale1>{{cite web|url=https://som.yale.edu/event/2016/05/conversation-with-ragy-thomas-ceo-founder-sprinklr |title=Sprinklr CEO Ragy Thomas Discusses Marketing in the Age of Social Media|website=Yale School of Management|date=2010-10-08 |accessdate=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://twitter.com/ragythomas Ragy Thomas on Twitter]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thomas, Ragy}}\n[[Category:American technology chief executives]]\n[[Category:New York University Stern School of Business alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4073:15:50db:908b:ecff:fe7e:c7f8", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Invalid)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ragy_Thomas"}
